            "answer_text": "It\u2019s an interesting question. I have worked as a translator, and I\u2019ve read a lot of literature in translation. I started translating almost as soon as I started having language lessons in school. I was compelled to seek out the literature to see what it was like. Years later, that\u2019s why I did a module of classical Greek to fill out the credits for a degree otherwise devoted to music. I don\u2019t really like the connotations of the word \u2018betray\u2019. It makes me think of John Le Carr\u00e9 novels, as if the translation is going to leave the original stranded in the death zone of monoglot indifference, where it\u2019ll be gunned down by the ruthless Grenzpolizei of the target reader\u2019s uninterest. (Some readers are going to be following this metaphor and going Wha\u2026) The translation is necessarily secondary to the original work, and can\u2019t exist without it, but the question needs to be framed more like: what in a work is translatable? What, if anything, are we missing, in the translation? Walter Benjamin\u2019s great 1921 essay \u2018The Task of the Translator\u2019, originally published as part of his translation of Baudelaire\u2019s Tableaux parisiens but available in English in Selected Writings Vol. 1: 1913\u20131926, gives a much more erudite and informed account of the translation process and its drawbacks and advantages than I could give. But I want to quote a passage that Benjamin quotes from the poet and philosopher Rudolf Pannwitz. Benjamin calls this \u2018the best comment on the theory of translation that has been published in Germany\u2019. Here\u2019s Pannwitz: Our translations, even the best ones, proceed from a mistaken premise. They want to turn Hindi, Greek, English into German instead of turning German into Hindi, Greek, English. Our translators have a far greater reverence for the usage of their own language than for the spirit of the foreign works \u2026 [ellipsis in original] The basic error of the translator is that he preserves the state in which his own language happens to be instead of allowing the language to be powerfully affected by the foreign tongue. Particularly when translating from a language very remote from his own, he must go back to the primal elements of language itself and penetrate to the point where work, image and tone converge. He must expand and deepen his language by means of the foreign language. [\u2026] I agree with Benjamin agreeing with Pannwitz. The worst translations are insufficiently irreverent about the target language. The best ones bring something new into the target language that wasn\u2019t there before. The translators of the Authorised Version of the Bible certainly did this, with the unfortunate side effect that an annoyingly large number of not very sophisticated Christians consider that translation to have more scriptural authority than the original. The KJV does indeed betray its original, with Exodus 20:13 infamously translated as Thou shall not kill, when everyone who knows the original knows that the Hebrew verb here means not \u2018kill\u2019 but \u2018murder\u2019, and refers to unlawful killing. And yet the KJV undoubtedly shaped the language to a great degree, contributing numerous phrases and rhythms without which we\u2019d be the poorer. Still, I don\u2019t know if betray is a good word. I think it elides the two-way nature of a good translation: the way it gives something to the source as well as the target language. Incidentally, for those that doubt I\u2019ve worked as a translator, credentials time:  From:  ",
